      <div class='hentry member_contribution' id='S5LV0636P0-00840'>
        <a name='S5LV0636P0_20020611_GCR_53'>  </a>
        <blockquote cite='http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/people/ms-patricia-scotland' class='contribution_text entry-content'>
          <a class='speech-permalink permalink' href='#S5LV0636P0_20020611_GCR_53' title='Link to this speech by Ms Patricia Scotland' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
          <cite class='member author entry-title'><a href="/people/ms-patricia-scotland" title="Ms Patricia Scotland">Baroness Scotland of Asthal</a></cite>
          <p class='first-para'>
            That is an enticing thought for us to consider. There are some solutions for cases on which the First Minister and Deputy First Minister cannot agree. Clause 5(7) provides that,
            <q>The First Minister and deputy First Minister must, on being informed by the Commission of the outcome of the reconsideration of its decision, appoint, or recommend for appointment, the person selected by the Commission after the reconsideration".</q>
            So, although they can send it back, the second recommendation made by the commission must be accepted. I hope that that provides a means out of the conundrum that the noble Lord so delighted us by suggesting.
          </p>
        </blockquote>
      </div>
      
      <div class='hentry member_contribution' id='S5LV0636P0-00841'>
